## **Class Description**

This course is a practical, hands-on exploration of physical interaction for designers. Students will examine how to interface objects and installations with the viewer’s body and ambient stimuli, such as motion, light, sound and intangible data. Using the open-source Arduino platform, the class will move through electrical theory, circuit design, microcontroller programming and sensors, as well as more advanced output, including motors, video and intercommunication between objects. *No previous programming or electronics experience is required.*

## **Learning Objectives**

* **Construct Basic Electronic Circuits**: Identify and assemble fundamental electronic components to build functional circuits.  
* **Design Interactive Experiences**: Create interactive systems incorporating sensors, lights, sounds, and movements.  
* **Program and Troubleshoot Embedded Circuits** using platforms such as Arduino or Raspberry Pi  
* **Fabricate Custom Enclosures**: Design and produce enclosures using materials such as paper, wood, acrylic, and 3D printing.  
* **Integrate Digital Services**: Connect physical projects to digital services and libraries, such as web APIs, Touchdesigner, Max/MSP, and p5.js

## **Requirements/Class Expectations**

Participation is mandatory for this course. The success of your participation requires a thoughtful approach to the readings, assignments, and selected projects due the following class. Students will represent their thoughts and ideas clearly and articulately, interacting with the class through shared reflection, critique, and collaboration. All work, including sketches, research, papers, and digital files, are presented in the course.

**Attendance**: Participation in group discussions and collaborative assignments during workshop sections are an important part of the course. More than two unexcused absences and you risk failing the course. If you need to be absent for any reason, please give **both** instructors at least 24 hours of advanced notice via **email**.

**Assignments**: Each week you’re expected to review and practice materials in lab assignments, complete project assignments, and document your progress and questions in your Physical Computing blog. There will be two group projects for midterm and final, which you will show on Week 7 and Week 1\.

**Documentation**: **Blog posts are due 23:59, the Monday before each class.** A good blog post should include ideation, design, circuit diagram/schematic, photos and videos of your process, and a showcase of the final result. Here’re a couple of example blogs from past students for inspiration: [Young Kim](https://tremendous-angora-935.notion.site/Young-s-Blog-17ab8f05f52b422b8f774fd8405fdcc8) (Notion), [Awanee Joshi](https://medium.com/@awaneemjoshi/list/awanees-physical-computing-blog-posts-5a2cc296e9f8) (Medium), [Jueun Jeon](https://www.jueunjeon.design/sva-blog/fall-2022/phys-comp.html) (page in personal website)

## **Policies**

### **Incomplete Grades**

In rare circumstances, students unable to complete required coursework in a given semester may receive the grade "Incomplete.” This decision is made by the instructor, student, and chair of the ixD program, and an Incomplete Grade form is generated and put on file with the department and the Registrar’s Office. This form is an agreement between the student and instructor specifying what work needs to be completed and when it is due. Any deviation from this agreement may result in a failing grade for the course. It is a student’s responsibility to follow up with the instructor and chair to have a grade changed from incomplete to pass. 

### **Academic Integrity**

Academic dishonesty will not be tolerated. All assignments must be the original work of the student, clearly distinguishing between their own ideas and those sourced from others. The MFA Interaction Design department defines plagiarism as follows:

1. **Generative AI Tools:** The use of generative AI tools (e.g., ChatGPT, DALL-E, Midjourney, etc.) to create content (text, images, code, etc.) is permitted only if the student provides appropriate citations and clearly distinguishes between AI-generated content and their own work. Failure to do so constitutes academic dishonesty.  
2. **Direct Copying:** Reproducing four or more consecutive words from any written, oral, or online source without proper citation.  
3. **Visual Reproduction:** Copying drawings, illustrations, tables, charts, or graphs from any source without appropriate reference.  
4. **Paraphrasing:** Rewriting someone else’s theories, ideas, concepts, statistics, factual data, or words without proper citation.

Students found to have committed an act of academic dishonesty will receive a failing grade for the assignment in question. More serious or repeated violations will be addressed according to the procedures outlined in the [SVA Handbook](https://sva.edu/life-at-sva/campus-life/sva-handbook).

### **Academic Progress**

Graduate students must maintain a minimum grade point average of 3.0 in order to remain in good academic standing. Students who do not meet these minimum requirements will be placed on academic probation, receive a letter specifying the terms of probation, and have their work monitored by the department. Receiving an incomplete or failing grade can place a student on academic probation. Students on academic probation are not eligible for scholarship renewal or Two semesters on academic probation, or not fulfilling the conditions of the probation letter, may result in dismissal from SVA.

### **Mid-Semester Evaluations**

Students who do not meet course requirements will receive a Mid-Semester Unsatisfactory Evaluation. This form may be given to a student for excessive absences, failure to complete required work or assignments in a satisfactory manner, or failure to participate in classroom work and activity. A student will receive written notification of a Mid-Semester Unsatisfactory Evaluation, as will the Department Chair, and the Graduate Advisor.

### **Students with Impairments and Disabilities**

In order to receive academic accommodations due to an impairment or disability, a student must first register with the Office of Disability Services (ODS). Students approved for accommodations will be given an ODS Accommodation Letter to submit to their instructors. If a student does not provide an ODS Accommodation Letter to their instructor, they will not be eligible to receive accommodations in that course. All instructors are required to adhere to SVA's policies regarding accommodations for students with disabilities. Students who have a need for academic accommodations, or suspect they may have an impairment or disability, should contact the ODS at 212.592.2282 or disabilityservices@sva.edu.

### **Attendance & Lateness**

Students are expected to attend and be on time for **all classes**. There is not an option to attend classes remotely. Students who arrive ten minutes or more after class begins are marked as late. **Three latenesses equal one absence**. If a student arrives more than 30 minutes late for class they may be marked as absent. Missing more than three classes can result in a failing grade for the course and potential academic probation. 

**No “Excused” Absences**  
No absences are considered excused for the purpose of this policy, regardless of the reason or an individual instructor's policy. This is an SVA policy upheld by our regional accreditors that requires a minimum number of instructional hours to receive academic credit. 

**Absences due to illness are not excused.**  
Students who are ill should not provide doctors' notes. If a student has extenuating health-related circumstances that may necessitate excessive absences the student may contact  [Disability Resources](https://sva.edu/life-at-sva/campus-life/health-and-safety/disability-resources) and [Student Health and Counseling](https://sva.edu/life-at-sva/campus-life/health-and-safety/health-counseling) Services. Both offices may be able to provide support and grant accommodations for excessive absences. It is a student's responsibility to seek accommodations. Staff in these offices will contact ixD faculty and staff if any accommodations are to be granted.  

### **Pronouns and Chosen Names**

Students may indicate their pronouns and preferred/chosen first name through MyServices; this information will then appear on class rosters (go to: [https://myservices.sva.edu/Student/UserProfile](https://myservices.sva.edu/Student/UserProfile) and select “Edit Personal Identity”).

Please let your instructor know the preferred name and pronouns by which you would like to be referred, if that information does not already appear on the roster. A student’s chosen name and pronouns should be respected at all times.

### **VFL Access**

Part of our class takes place at the Visible Futures Lab (VFL), a facility open to faculty and staff of SVA and all students of SVA graduate programs. Access to the VFL machines outside of the makerspace requires training and certification. Training sessions are offered for the wood shop, Shopbot (CNC gantry router), laser cutters and 3D printers and range from 1 to 3 hours.

All users must have an appointment before accessing the VFL (except classes). To book an appointment, visit the [appointments](https://www.vfl.sva.edu/appointments) page on VFL’s website.

More information visit the [VFL’s website](https://www.vfl.sva.edu/).

### **Desk Research: Midterm Assignment \#2, due 23:59 Monday, September 22nd**

Find **at least two sources** of information or examples for each category listed below.

* **Market Research**: Understand what is currently available on the market. Understand who is driving innovation, who they market their solutions to, and, if available, how they design and build their products.

* **Thought Leaders:** Identify people you’d like to talk to who are leaders in the community. We can help you get in touch with people for informational interviews as the semester progresses.

### **Initial Prototype: Midterm Assignment \#4, due 23:59 Monday, October 5th**

Building off your research and your paper prototypes, build an initial prototype using your ESP32 Feather microcontroller. This is a first version prototype and it will not be perfect or solve all parts of the problems your community is facing. At a minimum, your design needs to use the following: your ESP32 microcontroller, a sensor (e.g. gesture, motion, sound), and an actuator (e.g. motor, sound, light). 

At this point in the class, it is acceptable to build something that works under certain conditions or constraints. Please **be iterative and intentional** with your design. Avoid building out a fully fleshed out design with an enclosure or attempt complex multiple sensor inputs. 

Document the following for your build:

- The parts and components used  
- The code used for your sketch  
- The intended interaction (happy path) for your design

Take notes on the following:

- **Troubleshooting** you had to do, including the steps you took to address problems in your design  
- **Problems** that came up in playtesting your design  
- Any **constraints** such as power, connectivity, and failure points with the prototype

Reference Reading: 

- Initial Prototypes \- The First FitBit: [https://spectrum.ieee.org/fitbit](https://spectrum.ieee.org/fitbit)  
- Example of my work with Raspbery Pi 3 and Python: [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1RuPy-DXyvwP1\_uuzpQx7pJ8gg4ft0RnslZ7wTNUNsGw/edit?tab=t.0\#heading=h.9sinclaykxg5](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1RuPy-DXyvwP1_uuzpQx7pJ8gg4ft0RnslZ7wTNUNsGw/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.9sinclaykxg5)

### **Oct. 29th\_Week 9: Midterm Crit\!**

* Present your Midterm Project. Please use this presentation structure, emphasizing the time spent on your live demo, summarizing what the team learned from playtesting, and upcoming design iterations.
